slow Jenkins is very often a disk space problem. Jenkins stores everything (builds, logs, artifacts, workspaces), and it grows FAST.
Let’s safely free space step-by-step.

Step 1 — Check disk usage first
Run:
df -h
Look for the / partition. If it’s above 80–90%, Jenkins will slow down badly.
Now check what is eating space:
sudo du -h /var/lib/jenkins | sort -rh | head -20
This shows the biggest folders inside Jenkins.
Most of the time the space hogs are:
	• old build history
	• artifacts
	• workspace folders
	• logs

Step 2 — Clean old build history (BIGGEST WIN)
Jenkins stores every build forever unless you tell it not to.
Delete old builds:
sudo rm -rf /var/lib/jenkins/jobs/*/builds/*
This removes:
	• old console logs
	• old build metadata
	• test results
👉 This alone can free GBs of space.

Step 3 — Delete old Jenkins workspaces
Each job keeps a workspace copy of your repo.
Clean them:
sudo rm -rf /var/lib/jenkins/workspace/*
These can become HUGE.

Step 4 — Remove old build artifacts
Artifacts are files Jenkins keeps after builds (zips, jars, images).
Clean them:
sudo rm -rf /var/lib/jenkins/jobs/*/builds/*/archive/*

Step 5 — Clear Jenkins logs
Logs grow forever.
sudo rm -rf /var/log/jenkins/*
Also clean system logs:
sudo journalctl --vacuum-time=7d
This keeps only 7 days of logs.

Step 6 — Clean package cache
Amazon Linux keeps package cache files.
sudo dnf clean all

Step 7 — Restart Jenkins
After cleanup:
sudo systemctl restart jenkins
You should notice the dashboard is much faster.

Step 8 — VERY IMPORTANT (prevent this happening again)
Inside Jenkins UI:
	1. Open a job
	2. Click Configure
	3. Scroll to Build Discarder
	4. Check:
Discard old builds
Set:
	• Keep builds: 10
	• Keep artifacts: 5
Do this for your jobs so Jenkins auto-cleans itself.

💡 Pro tip (huge performance boost)
If your disk is small (like 8GB EC2), Jenkins will always struggle.
Recommended minimum for Jenkins servers:
	• 20–30GB disk
2GB RAM
